post_text:
This is an update to our current situation regarding the CoronaVirus and our long term plan in the Wahpeton School District. Teachers and administration have been working this week to ensure the safety for students and staff while continuing to offer academic and physical needs should a long term plan come into play.

The Governor has not given us any information regarding school closures for next week. If we hear from the state that school is canceled for weeks to come, staff is currently working on a plan to provide education outside the school setting. We will continue to update all of you with future plans.

We appreciate your patience and understanding during this difficult time. Continue to keep yourself and your family safe.

Rick Jacobson
Superintendent

The Wahpeton School will have breakfast and lunch available during the week during this time off. These meals will be grab-n-go (you pick up the bag and go home to eat). These meals will be free for all students K-12. Each student needs to come and pick up their bags.
Food pickup options:

Option 1: Breakfast and lunch bags will be available at the Elementary School DOOR #9 only. Breakfast will be from 8:30 am to 9:30 am and lunch available at 11am to 12:30 pm. Or

Option 2: We will be delivering meals according to the bus stops. A schedule is attached and will be on the web site. These times are approximate and can be adjusted. We will deliver one time a day with both a lunch bag and breakfast bag. If you have questions please call the school office.

https://wahpetonschools.org/ourpages/auto/2020/3/16/53425890/WPS%20Food%20Service%20Stops%203-16-2020.pdf

At the kickoff assembly we played our version of the ‚ÄúMasked Singer‚Äù except we had masked dancers! Students had a blast trying to guess their identity!

You can learn more about the Great Kindness Challenge @ thegreatkindnesschallenge.com

text:
Middle School Disability Awareness Week
Day 2 and 3- each 8th grade student spent about 30-40 minutes in a wheelchair completing daily tasks.
Day 4- Mrs.Goerger spoke to each class about the struggles and realizations she has had since being disabled!

post_text: Day 1 of the Middle School Disability Awareness Week was a huge success! The NDSCS 2nd Year Occupational Therapy students did a fabulous job teaching our kids about many types of disabilities. Thanks to Missi Twidell for bringing all your students over! We even had North Dakota Superintendent Kirsten Baesler join us!
